I have here the kg-99 pistol.Let me explain a brief history on these guns.George Kellgren who know owns Kel-Tec designed a open bolt version of this gun called the KG-9.only about 2500 were produced before the ATF banned them.He then redesigned the gun into a closed bolt version called the kg-99 ONLY produced for one year.His compant was called interdynamic usa.There was an interdynamic in Sweden also.He sold his half of the company to a man last name Garcia which in turn renamed the company Intratec and renamed the kg-99 into the Tec 9 which also became the tec dc -9 and ab-10.So what i have is the kg-99 closed bolt only produced for a year under George kellgren.The quality control went downhill once he sold the compant and once people started suing intratec to which they eventually went out of business.This gun was bought from Gat guns years ago

title: For Sale:  Indy Trading Post **READ**
postcontent:
So I made a post this morning, WTB a colt defender.  A Matt who is a salesman at Indy Trading Post here in Indy, replies to my ad & says they have 1 in stock.

So I go to their website to see a price & it's listed @ $1,044.00  (go to shop online, it's the last link on their page)
So I call, excited to finally find this gun at the price I wanted to pay, Matt then tells me the gun is $1,299.00!!  I asked Matt why the website says $1,044.00 & he suggested I call back & talk to the owner after 6pm tonight....so I did.  Matt states the gun costs was $1,000.00 & they like to make at least $150.00 on a gun of this quality & shoots me a price of $1150.00.  So again I question the advertised price VS what I am being quoted & he said he would talk to the owner & I should call tonight.

so I call at 6:30, guy that answered the phone, puts me on hold after I explain the story to him & he tells me he spoke to the owner & the price of the gun is $1299.00, I then question him & ask him why they have it advertised at $1044 & the guy tells me they dont list prices on the website (which I have it printed out)  he then proceeds to tell me it's an error.
I then ask him if they'd be willing to work with me on a price between what was advertised online VS what the tell me on the phone of $1299.00 & I was told NOPE.  IT's $1299.00 & that's that.
The guy then proceeds to tell me it must be another gun...I mean comon a BNIB COlt Defender is exactly the same as another BNIB Colt Defender.

Absolutely BAD business.....  horrible that they wouldnt even try to negotiate a price...nothing but a "sorry"...

Not sure how long this post will stay active before it get's marked as spam...but jsut thought I'd do my part in spreading the word on HOW some local dealers operate.
Not to mention the fact that a BNIB Defender can be found on Gunbroker, gunsamerica...etc for less than $1100.00   just pisses me off!!!
Guess I'll just have to keep looking....

title: For Sale:  Several guns/ammo at FAIR MSRP PRICES
postcontent:
It is our job as a firearm community to weed out the bad eggs trying to make a quick buck and/or rip people off. I have made a list of fair prices, even considering the current market climate, so that people can be educated on what things retail for if you have a small amount of patience. 

If you see something grossly overpriced, please flag it as overpriced. There is a flag option of every post, just mark overpriced items and move on so we can get some sense of normalcy back 5 months after the run up on guns and ammo started. 
I understand some things command a SMALL premium since they are hard to find, but double and triple price is not reasonable, and we need to work together to flag these people away.

The list:	
POPULAR AMMO:
5.56/.223 Ammo: 
30-35 cents per round for steel case
40 cents per round for bulk brass FMJ
50-60 cents per round for hunting stuff	

9mm Ammo:
30-40 cents per round for steel case and bulk brass FMJ
40-60 cents per round for normal hollow points

.22LR rimfire ammo
.04 to .06 a round for bulk lead and lead hollow points
.08 cents per round for CCI and quality stuff

The reality is if you are patient and put a little time into it, you can get most ammo types for .30-.50 cents a round. Some Hollow points and carry ammo do go for more. 

POPULAR GUNS:
AR-15’s and M-4’s: 800-1200 dollars is MSRP on most models.

AR-10’s. You can find these for 1200-1400 dollars retail easily.

Mini 14- 800-1100 depending on the model

Glocks: 500-625 depending on the model. Do not pay more than this for any glock. 

Mossberg 500: Most models sell for right at $350-400. I wouldn’t pay more than this.

10/22: These sell for anywhere from $220-270 depending on the stock and barrel, new in box. Be patient and flag 400 dollar ones on here. They are grossly overpriced. 

1911: These can go from as low as 400 to as high as 2000, so BE SURE and RESEARCH the model before you buy. 

Please feel free to repost this in other towns/areas if you want, and spread the word. If you are sick of seeing 800 dollar Assault Rifles selling for 2000, and 1200 dollar AR-10’s for 2500, please TAKE ACTION!!!! FLAG PEOPLE AS OVERPRICED! Feel free to send them a message letting them know how overpriced they are as well. They are ruining local gun communities.

title: For Sale:  Reasonably priced gun stuff!
postcontent:
It is our job as a firearm community to weed out the bad eggs trying to make a quick buck and/or rip people off. I have made a list of fair prices, even considering the current market climate, so that people can be educated on what things retail for if you have a small amount of patience. 
If you see something grossly overpriced, please flag it as overpriced. There is a flag option of every post, just mark overpriced items and move on so we can get some sense of normalcy back 5 months after the run up on guns and ammo started. 
I understand some things command a SMALL premium since they are hard to find, but double and triple price is not reasonable, and we need to work together to flag these people away.
The list:	
POPULAR AMMO:
5.56/.223 Ammo: 
30-35 cents per round for steel case
40 cents per round for bulk brass FMJ
50-60 cents per round for hunting stuff	

9mm Ammo:
30-40 cents per round for steel case and bulk brass FMJ
40-60 cents per round for normal hollow points

.22LR rimfire ammo
.04 to .06 a round for bulk lead and lead hollow points
.08 cents per round for CCI and quality stuff
The reality is if you are patient and put a little time into it, you can get most ammo types for .30-.50 cents a round. Some Hollow points and carry ammo do go for more. 

POPULAR GUNS:
AR-15’s and M-4’s: 800-1200 dollars is MSRP on most models. DPMS, Bushmaster, Doublestar, colt etc rarely break the 1200 mark retail. 
AR-10’s. You can find these for 1200-1400 dollars retail easily from BUDS, they come in stock once a week or two. 
Mini 14- 800-1100 depending on the model
Glocks: 500-625 depending on the model. Do not pay more than this for any glock. 
Mossberg 500: Most models sell for right at $350-400. I wouldn’t pay more than this. 
10/22: These sell for anywhere from $220-270 depending on the stock and barrel, new in box. Be patient and flag 400 dollar ones on here. They are grossly overpriced. 
1911: These can go from as low as 400 to as high as 2000, so BE SURE and RESEARCH the model before you buy.

Please feel free to repost this in other towns/areas if you want, and spread the word. If you are sick of seeing 800 dollar Assault Rifles selling for 2000 and 1200 dollar AR-10’s for 2500, please TAKE ACTION!!!! FLAG PEOPLE AS OVERPRICED! Feel free to send them a message letting them know how overpriced they are as well. They are ruining local gun communities.

Troy Battle Mags are very similiar to P-Mags, with a few exceptions. A lot of people think they are superior to P-Mags for some or all of these reasons.
